events.name: SRLx Post Conference Discussions and Future Events Planning
events.description:
Howdy,

Thank you for presenting your research projects at SRLx Event.

It was exciting to see how you are using Machine Learning on Android platform to solve various real-world problems.

In this meetup, we are looking forward to hearing about your experiences on presenting at SRLx.

Also, we will be discussing the schedule for the Android Development sessions that the chapter will be organizing in Jan-Feb 2018.

Thank you.

Vijay Rajanna and Larry Powell.

GDG TAMU.
events.how_to_find_us: Sketch Recognition Lab, Teague 326, Texas A&M University.

events.name: GDG and SIGCHI Information and Lab Demo
events.description:
Howdy,

During this meetup, we are going to provide information about the TAMU Google Developer Group (GDG TAMU) and SIGCHI organizations. From there we have speakers from several Human-Computer Interaction Research Labs that will provide information about their lab and a few projects that they are currently working on.

Please join us for these great talks and some pizza.

Sponsor: Computer Science and Engineering Graduate Students Association (CSEGSA).

Regards,
GDG TAMU

events.name: Holiday Party - Google Developers Group
events.description:
Howdy!

Texas A&M Google Developers Group (GDG TAMU) cordially invites you to our ANNUAL HOLIDAY PARTY. We will have a delicious Indian lunch buffet, gaming consoles, and board games!!!

This is an RSVP only event, and you MUST RSVP by December 10th.
We are looking forward to seeing you at the event.

Location: HRBB, Grad Student Lounge (Room 310)

For questions contact:
Vijay Rajanna - [masked] | Larry Powell - [masked]

events.name: Capstone Poster Presentation
events.description:
Howdy,

Students from Capstone course will be presenting their research works as posters at this event. A majority of these projects use various technologies offered by Google and are in the domain of Human-Computer Interaction. You are invited to review and provide feedback on these early-stage research works. This event is aimed at preparing the students for the upcoming Texas A&M Student Research Week.
